2. Understanding the Seed Mechanism\par
Since all campaign data is stored on-device (localStorage/local database), we need a way to initialize it without making the GM type out 50 NPCs and 100 connections by hand. That is the Seed Mechanism:\par
\par
Mermaid diagram\par
Step 1 (Backend): You write your campaign notes and run your Python script (_build_web.py). It scans your documents and compiles web.json (listing all entities, aliases, tags, authored edges, and co-occurrence scores).\par
Step 2 (Frontend): In the GM App, you click "Seed Campaign" and upload that web.json.\par
Step 3 (Integration): The app reads the file, parses the arrays, and saves them to the browser's local store.\par
The Result: Instantly, the app's database matches your written notes. The Compendium now knows every NPC and location, and the force-graph has its structure.\par
3. The Digital Dashboard vs. Analog Runsheet (Correction Acknowledged)\par
You are entirely right. I mischaracterized the runsheet. If you are running the session using WordPad/RTF side-by-side, the app should not try to replicate or replace that text document flow directly. Instead, the app should be designed for digital co-piloting:\par
\par
Active Roster Panel: Quick-glance cards of the players with their current HP/FP, passive stats (like Wizard Sight), and active conditions.\par
Campaign Clocks & Chapters: Visual progress dials (e.g. tracking the Strain 2.0 timeline or Dagon's Unmaking) that the GM can tick up or down.\par
Encounter Panel: Quick-launch buttons to spawn enemies and manage initiative.\par
NPC Quick Reference: A list of NPCs currently in the scene, which the GM can tap to reveal disposition, key hooks, or relationship changes.\par
The app is the dashboard (handling the mechanics and links), while the WordPad runsheet is your script (handling the narrative flow).\par
\par
4. Combat Tracker as a Sub-Feature\par
Exactly. Combat Mode is an addition you drop into when initiative is rolled\f2\emdash not the home screen. The core of the GM app is the Campaign Dashboard and the Lore Web. When combat starts, you click "Enter Combat Mode", the dashboard slides down, and the combat tracker takes over. When the fight ends, you close it and return to the campaign view.\par
\par
5. Rich Text / Note-Taking Options\par
For the session notes editor in the app, a plain <textarea> (like the player sheet has) is too limited for a GM who needs color-coding and formatting.\par
\par
Since you write your runsheets in WordPad/RTF, here are the three best options for how we can handle rich notes/runsheets in the app:\par
\par
Option A: A Styled WYSIWYG Rich Text Editor (Recommended)\par
We implement a lightweight, styled Rich Text editor (using a package like TipTap or a custom-built React wrapper) directly in the app.\par
\par
How it looks: It looks like a clean, parchment-themed editor with standard formatting buttons (Bold, Italic, lists) and custom styles (e.g., a "Read Aloud" button that formats text in blue/italic, or a "GM Note" button that formats in maroon).\par
The Magic: As you type, the editor can actively check for matches in your Lore Web. If you type the name "Danica", it highlights her name and lets you hover over it to see her reference card without leaving your notes.\par
Option B: Split-Screen File Viewer\par
If you prefer writing in external WordPad, we can build a Document Viewer panel. You drag-and-drop your .rtf file into the app, and the app renders it in a styled window side-by-side with your GM controls. It extracts the text structure but lets you keep everything in one window.\par
\par
Option C: Structured Markdown Editor\par
You write in standard markdown (using #, *, etc.), and the app displays a live split-screen preview rendering it as parchment blocks. Very lightweight, highly compatible, and easy to export as .md or .txt.\par
